					<td>
					

						<div class="postbody"><div class="quotetitle"><b>Quote:</b></div><div class="quotecontent">I wonder if I could use the 9 sprite trick tokumaru mentioned to detect the beginning of a frame, and THEN turn off graphics, then wait with cycle timed code, then turn them back on. Is that another possible way to eliminate dot crawl as well? Or is that exactly the trick tokumaru mentioned and I'm now understanding all of the edge cases it addresses?</div><br /><br />That's pretty much what I've done for my own game recently - you can find some interesting points about how I solved it at the end of <a href="http://forums.nesdev.com/viewtopic.php?f=9&amp;t=4647&amp;start=75" class="postlink">this</a> thread.<br /><br />As the topic suggests, disabling rendering triggers a nasty bug on NTSC NESes which causes corruption of sprites the next time you enable it. But if you turn off rendering around dot 330 then AFAICT this will always affect sprites 2 and 3 only, so you can avoid the sprite corruption by just starting your sprite page write pointer at a higher offset. But I cannot stress enough that if you write code where timing is this important to avoid a hardware quirk you should in no way rely on emulators for testing its correctness.<br /><br />Also, if you have a sprite#0 hit that gets triggered in every frame then you don't need those 9 blank sprites you mentioned since you can wait for the start of vblank just by waiting for this flag to get cleared again. <img src="./images/smilies/icon_smile.gif" alt=":)" title="Smile" /></div>

